ons in the French case, examining national elitism, neo-colonialism, and other exclusionary discourses, as well as discussing for the first time the subculture of cinema around the extreme right Front National. Key works from directors such as Michel Audiard, Jean-Luc Godard, Jean-Pierre Melville, Marcel Pagnol, Jean Renoir, Jacques Tati, François Truffaut, and others provide a rich body of evidence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aMotion picturesxHistoryx20th centuryxFrance. 0aMotion picturesxPolitical aspectsxHistoryx20th centuryxFrance. 0aMotion picturesxPolitical aspectszFrancexHistoryy20th century. 0aMotion picturesxPolitical aspects. 0aMotion pictureszFrancexHistoryy20th century. 0aMotion pictures. 0aNationalism in motion pictures. 0aPatriotism in motion picturesxFrancexHistory. 0aPatriotism in motion pictures. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311099823840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178238366640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782383666423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782383666/original  a978-3-11-099823-8  Berghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK